Through the examination of the graph, no pattern can be seen in the lap times of the drivers across the decades. No significant fluctuations in lap times were observed over the years. The average lap times of the drivers stayed right around 100 seconds, with the majority of the times being around that number as well. No major outlines were observed, which would not change our findings, since they depend on safety car implications, that might involve crashes, flags, etc. 

## Track Approach

For this part of the analysis, we are going to dig deeper, and focus on the finishers in the front row. We will filter the data set in order to keep the drivers that finished first, second, or third. Then, we will take their average for each circuit. To have a more accurate analysis, we are going to focus on the four circuits that have been in the calendar since the beginning of Formula 1, in the 1950s: British Grand Prix (Silverstone), Monaco Grand Prix (Monaco), Belgian Grand Prix (Spa), and Italian Grand Prix (Monza).


